Package com.github.tommyettinger.ds

Class HolderSet<T,​K>

java.lang.Object
com.github.tommyettinger.ds.HolderSet<T,​K>
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.util.Collection<T>, java.util.Set<T>
Direct Known Subclasses:
HolderOrderedSet
public class HolderSet<T,​K>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.util.Set<T>, java.io.Serializable
An unordered set where the items are objects but access to items is done with a specific key component held by each item, and the component is extracted from an item by a given Function. Neither null items nor null keys are allowed. No allocation is done except when growing the table size. The function is called the extractor, and is often a method reference.
Some operations are different here from a normal Set; contains(Object) expects a K key, and remove(Object) does as well. You can use get(Object) to go back to a T value from a K key.
This class is currently a work in progress, and documentation may be inaccurate.

    • getExtractor

      @Nullable public java.util.function.Function<T,​K> getExtractor()
      Gets the function this uses to extract keys from items. This may be null if HolderSet() was used to construct this object (or technically if HolderSet(HolderSet) was used to copy a HolderSet with an invalid extractor); in that case, this cannot have items added, removed, or inserted until a valid extractor is set with setExtractor(Function).
      Returns:
      the extractor function this uses to get keys from items

    • setExtractor

      public void setExtractor​(java.util.function.Function<T,​K> extractor)
      Sets the function this will use to extract keys from items; this will only have an effect if the extractor function is currently null/invalid. This is typically needed if HolderSet() was used to construct the HolderSet, but can also be required if HolderSet(HolderSet) was used to copy another HolderSet with an invalid extractor. All other cases should require the extractor function to be specified at construction-time.
      Parameters:
      extractor - a Function that takes a T and gets a unique K from it; often a method reference

    • place

      protected int place​(java.lang.Object item)
      Returns an index >= 0 and <= mask for the specified item, which here should be a K.

      The default behavior uses Fibonacci hashing; it simply gets the Object.hashCode() of item, multiplies it by a specific long constant related to the golden ratio, and makes an unsigned right shift by shift before casting to int and returning. This can be overridden to hash item differently, though all implementors must ensure this returns results in the range of 0 to mask, inclusive. If nothing else is changed, then unsigned-right-shifting an int or long by shift will also restrict results to the correct range.

      Parameters:
      item - a non-null Object; its hashCode() method should be used by most implementations.

    • locateKey

      protected int locateKey​(java.lang.Object key)
      Returns the index of the key if already present, else ~index for the next empty index. This can be overridden to compare for equality differently than Object.equals(Object). This expects key to be a K object, not a T item, and will extract keys from existing items to compare against.

      If source is not easily available and you want to override this, the reference source is: 

           protected int locateKey (Object key) {
         T[] keyTable = this.keyTable;
         for (int i = place(key); ; i = i + 1 & mask) {
             T other = keyTable[i];
             if (other == null) {
                 return ~i; // Always negative; means empty space is available at i.
             }
             if (key.equals(extractor.apply(other))) // If you want to change how equality is determined, do it here.
             {
                 return i; // Same key was found.
             }
         }
     }
      Parameters:
      key - a non-null Object that should probably be a K

    • shrink

      public void shrink​(int maximumCapacity)
      Reduces the size of the backing arrays to be the specified capacity / loadFactor, or less. If the capacity is already less, nothing is done. If the set contains more items than the specified capacity, the next highest power of two capacity is used instead.

    • clear

      public void clear​(int maximumCapacity)
      Clears the set and reduces the size of the backing arrays to be the specified capacity / loadFactor, if they are larger. The reduction is done by allocating new arrays, though for large arrays this can be faster than clearing the existing array.

    • clear

      public void clear()
      Clears the set, leaving the backing arrays at the current capacity. When the capacity is high and the population is low, iteration can be unnecessarily slow. clear(int) can be used to reduce the capacity.

    • toArray

      public <E> E[] toArray​(E[] a)
      Returns an array containing all of the elements in this set; the runtime type of the returned array is that of the specified array. If the set fits in the specified array, it is returned therein. Otherwise, a new array is allocated with the runtime type of the specified array and the size of this set.
      Implementation is mostly copied from GWT, but uses Arrays.copyOf() instead of their internal APIs.
      Specified by:
      toArray in interface java.util.Collection<T>
      Specified by:

      Type Parameters:

      Parameters:

      Returns:
      an array containing all the elements in this set
